bug.short_desc: [DataBinding] Ensure that getterCalled() is invoked correctly in WritableList

long_desc.thetext:
We need to clean up WritableList as its getterCalled() invocation is somewhat sporatic. Changes that need to be made:
* setters should not invoke getterCalled(); this means all add(..) and remove(...) methods. * iterator() should invoke getterCalled() (ObservableList) * next() and hasNext() on the iterator should not invoke getterCalled() (ObservableList)
The idea was previously that because add*(...) and remove*(...) returned a value then the state was retrieved thus getterCalled() should be invoked. But for the sake of simplicity these will be removed; we can always add them back later. But in removing the calls to getterCalled() we need to ensure that the current realm is still checked.
We also need to ensure that @TrackedGetter is documented in IObservableList when getterCalled() is invoked.

bug.short_desc: Add a dedicated "Open URL" menu item

long_desc.thetext:
Background
At present, we rely on windows specific behavior in the Open File dialog. This is bad for two reasons: 1. The information on where the actual document was located is lost. Windows will download the URL contents to the local disk and then pass a handle to the temporary file that it created. That behavior makes it impossible to, for instance, allow relative URL's for the RMAP or property files. 2. It doesn't make non-windows users very happy.
Solution We add a decicated "Open URL" menu item to the Buckminster menu. It will perform of course also download things to your local disk. The difference will be that it will work on all platforms and it will retain the original location.

org.eclipse.core.commands.ExecutionException: The parameter string could not be converted to an object at org.eclipse.core.commands.ExecutionEvent.getObjectParameterForExecution(ExecutionEvent.java:188) at org.eclipse.ui.internal.ide.handlers.OpenResourceHandler.execute(OpenResourceHandler.java:88) at org.eclipse.ui.internal.handlers.HandlerProxy.execute(HandlerProxy.java:151) at org.eclipse.core.commands.Command.executeWithChecks(Command.java:461) at org.eclipse.core.commands.ParameterizedCommand.executeWithChecks(ParameterizedCommand.java:424) at org.eclipse.ui.internal.cheatsheets.CommandRunner.executeCommand(CommandRunner.java:67)

Yes, this is a problem, currently the cheat sheet framework does not have a mechanism to disable or enable a step based on whether a rprevious step was completed or skipped. Copying Mike Pawlowski to see if he has any ideas for this particular cheat sheet.

For this particular cheat sheet, the failure is a result of not completing the new plug-in project wizard correctly (e.g. the plug-in project is not created). As a result, the subsequent command executed to open its plug-in manifest file in an editor fails.

Mylar for Eclipse 3.3 Features Mylar Task List (Required) 0.9.2

I ran a tool that compares the current I-builds with 3.2.1 to ensure that our qualifiers are incrementing appropriately for update sites. This tool will be part of the next integration build. Anyways, I noticed this
3.2.1 pde.doc.user is org.eclipse.pde.doc.user_3.2.1.v20060816-0800 current I-build I20061205-1200 pde.doc.user is org.eclipse.pde.doc.user_3.2.0.v20060918-0010
3.2.1 org.eclipse.pde is org.eclipse.pde_3.2.1.v20060810-0800 current I-build I20061205-1200 org.eclipse.pde_3.2.0.v20061101-0010

bug.short_desc: Support for new launcher organization

long_desc.thetext:
Because the launcher is being re-organized the build scripts will have to be adapted: Currently the exes are included in the build by: - getting the platform-launcher project out of cvs, - renaming it into org.eclipse.platform.launchers - having the platform feature referencing the launchers with relative paths
To adapt to the new structure we would need to: - use the org.eclipse.equinox.executable project where platform-launcher was.
Also the startup.jar is no longer necessary at the root of eclipse and no longer needs to be built. FYI it is replaced by a real plugin, build like a real plugin and included like a real plugin. The name of this plugin is org.eclipse.equinox.launcher.

Created an attachment (id=55409) Patch to the org.eclipse.sdk-feature
Remove references to startup.jar Added the launcher plug-in and its fragments.
CC'ing Andrew since he is the one doing the real work and will know when things will be ready for running test builds.

Created an attachment (id=55411) Patch to the map file
The current patch to the map file points to entries in the equinox incubator.

Created an attachment (id=55776) SDK-Feature Patch
Attached is an update sdk-feature patch. It is similar to Pascal's in that the launcher bundle & fragments are added to the RCP feature. In addition, all references to org.eclipse.platform.launchers in the root files are replaced with org.eclipse.equinox.executable.
I have already released changes to the equinox-incubator map file.

Created an attachment (id=55779) EclipseBuilder Patch
This patch is on the eclipse builder and replaces references to platform-launcer and org.eclipse.platform.launchers with org.eclipse.equinox.executable
Running a test build with these changes now.
Fixed.

bug.short_desc: CrossReferenceAdapter may trigger a resolve because it calls eIsSet on derived features

long_desc.thetext: GMF's CrossReferenceAdapter will call eIsSet() on derived features which could cause a resolve. To avoid this, I am adding a check for derived features. This is also a performance enhancement.
Made the change to CrossReferenceAdapter in gmf_R1_0_maintenance and gmf_head.

bug.short_desc: Can not use Scale on X-axis for area chart.

long_desc.thetext:
You can not use scale for area chart on X-axis (if if it is linear and has number in it) that result to the following behavior.
1.the origin of the axis is not a round number 2. Major grid is not controllable and for many data points looks ugly
You can control thin in scatter plot but by some reason can not do it in area chart (as well as probably the other types as well).
I think it should be controllable for all charts as long as X-axis is either linear (numbers) or dates.
Otherwise area charts looks ugly and unprofessional.
PS. I can fix the problem myself if someone gives me guidance where to look and what should I do approximately.
This should be fixed in 2.2
*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of bug 161579 ***
